        <!-- Legend -->
        <text x="200" y="235" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.35">BFS from A: frontier expands one level at a time</text>
      </svg>
    </div>

    <h3>Adjacency list representation</h3>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Graph as adjacency list
; Each vertex maps to its list of neighbors

(define graph
  (list (list "A" "B" "C")
        (list "B" "A" "D" "E")
        (list "C" "A" "F" "G")
        (list "D" "B")
        (list "E" "B" "F")
        (list "F" "C" "E")
        (list "G" "C")))

(define (neighbors g v)
  (let ((entry (assoc v g)))
    (if entry (cdr entry) (list))))

(display "Neighbors of A: ") (display (neighbors graph "A")) (newline)
(display "Neighbors of B: ") (display (neighbors graph "B"))
`} />

    <h3>Breadth-first search</h3>
    <p>BFS uses a queue. It visits all vertices at distance d before any at distance d+1. This gives shortest paths in unweighted graphs.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; BFS: explore level by level using a queue

(define graph
  (list (list "A" "B" "C")
        (list "B" "A" "D" "E")
        (list "C" "A" "F" "G")
        (list "D" "B")
        (list "E" "B" "F")
        (list "F" "C" "E")
        (list "G" "C")))

(define (neighbors g v)
  (let ((entry (assoc v g)))
    (if entry (cdr entry) (list))))

(define (bfs g start)
  (let loop ((queue (list start))
             (visited (list start))
             (order (list)))
    (if (null? queue)
        (reverse order)
        (let* ((v (car queue))
               (rest (cdr queue))
               (nbrs (neighbors g v))
               (new (filter (lambda (n) (not (member n visited))) nbrs)))
          (loop (append rest new)
                (append visited new)
                (cons v order))))))

(display "BFS from A: ")
(display (bfs graph "A"))
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# BFS in Python
from collections import deque

graph = {
    'A': ['B', 'C'], 'B': ['A', 'D', 'E'],
    'C': ['A', 'F', 'G'], 'D': ['B'],
    'E': ['B', 'F'], 'F': ['C', 'E'], 'G': ['C']
}

def bfs(graph, start):
    visited = {start}
    queue = deque([start])
    order = []
    while queue:
        v = queue.popleft()
        order.append(v)
        for n in graph[v]:
            if n not in visited:
                visited.add(n)
                queue.append(n)
    return order

print(f"BFS from A: {bfs(graph, 'A')}")
`} />
    </div>

    <h3>Depth-first search</h3>
    <p>DFS uses a stack (or recursion). It explores as deep as possible before backtracking. Useful for topological sort, cycle detection, and connected components.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; DFS: explore depth-first using recursion

(define graph
  (list (list "A" "B" "C")
        (list "B" "A" "D" "E")
        (list "C" "A" "F" "G")
        (list "D" "B")
        (list "E" "B" "F")
        (list "F" "C" "E")
        (list "G" "C")))

(define (neighbors g v)
  (let ((entry (assoc v g)))
    (if entry (cdr entry) (list))))

(define (dfs g start)
  (let loop ((stack (list start))
             (visited (list))
             (order (list)))
    (if (null? stack)
        (reverse order)
        (let ((v (car stack))
              (rest (cdr stack)))
          (if (member v visited)
              (loop rest visited order)
              (let ((nbrs (neighbors g v)))
                (loop (append nbrs rest)
                      (cons v visited)
                      (cons v order))))))))

(display "DFS from A: ")
(display (dfs graph "A"))
`} />

